From: Joey Eamigh <55670930+JoeyEamigh@users.noreply.github.com>
Subject: [PATCH] input: zero cursor sprite alpha on pointer_set_cursor

The bridgething image is a kiosk that exposes a rotary scroll wheel as
a wl_pointer (REL_HWHEEL -> wl_pointer.axis), which causes chromium to
call wl_pointer.set_cursor with its own bitmap. The end result we want
on the panel is no visible cursor at all; we get there today by
alpha-zeroing pointer->sprite from a frame_signal listener in an
out-of-tree weston module.

That listener runs after the renderer has already painted one frame
with the freshly-created sprite at the default alpha=1.0, so on the
very first set_cursor for any given client there is a one-frame flash
of cursor pixels before suppression catches up. On a 60 Hz panel that
flash is ~16 ms - small but visibly distracting on every focus enter
that follows a tap or other focus-establishing event.

Set sprite alpha to 0.0f the moment the sprite is (re)created. Renderer
draws zero pixels for the sprite on the very first frame, no race. The
out-of-tree frame_signal listener is responsible for raising alpha back
to 1.0 if and when a remote-viewer seat (e.g. weston-vnc's per-peer
"VNC Client") is present on the compositor and the panel's behaviour
should track the remote's expectation of a visible cursor.

Upstream-Status: Inappropriate [downstream policy]
Signed-off-by: Joey Eamigh <55670930+JoeyEamigh@users.noreply.github.com>
---
 libweston/input.c | 1 +
 1 file changed, 1 insertion(+)

diff --git a/libweston/input.c b/libweston/input.c
--- a/libweston/input.c
+++ b/libweston/input.c
@@ -3593,6 +3593,7 @@ pointer_set_cursor(struct wl_client *client, struct wl_resource *resource,
 		weston_surface_set_label_func(surface,
 					    pointer_cursor_surface_get_label);
 		pointer->sprite = weston_view_create(surface);
+		weston_view_set_alpha(pointer->sprite, 0.0f);
 	}

 	pointer->hotspot = weston_coord_surface(x, y, surface);
